897 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN JERUSALEM, THE LIGHT OF PEACE FLICKERS; 
</P>
<P>
MIDDLE EAST: THE HOLY CITY IS RELATIVELY TRANQUIL, BUT THE INTIFADA DEFIES 
SETTLEMENT. AND THE BUSH ADMINISTRATION HAS BEEN MORE HINDRANCE THAN HELP. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEANE KIRKPATRICK, Jeane Kirkpatrick is a syndicated columnist based in 
Washington. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
JERUSALEM 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Whom the gods would destroy they first tempt to resolve the Arab-Israeli 
conflict, Irving Kristol once observed. 
</P>
<P>
George Bush and James Baker should be extremely wary of the political quicksand 
into which they are attempting to lead Israelis, Egyptians and 
still-unidentified Palestinians. The probability is that Bush and Baker will 
fail in their attempt to promote an Israeli-Palestinian dialogue desired by 
neither Israelis nor Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
The Administration has already strained Israeli trust and American good will. 
The White House's recent very public delay in granting a presidential 
appointment to Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir was an effort to pressure 
and embarrass Israel. The refusal of the United States to provide Israel clear 
and complete information about Egypt's responses to Baker's five points creates 
more mistrust. The extraordinary request by the United States that leaders of 
the Israeli opposition Labor Party be included in Israel's team preparing for 
talks in Washington was widely regarded as insulting. 
</P>
<P>
Why have Bush and Baker acted this way? Are they trying to demonstrate to a 
disbelieving Arab world that the United States is neutral between Israelis and 
the Palestinians? Do they want to intensify disagreement within Shamir's 
government in the hope that it will be replaced by a more tractable Labor 
government? Were they unable to get from Egypt a response to Baker's five 
points that would be minimally acceptable to the government of Israel? Is it 
possible that the Bush/Baker team, which is correctly sensitive to Mikhail 
Gorbachev's pride and Deng Xiao-ping's pride, does not understand that Israelis 
also are proud? 
</P>
<P>
Always poor, prospects for settlement have become even bleaker in the last 
year, complicated by the Palestine Liberation Organization's declaration of an 
independent state, by the withdrawal of King Hussein from a role in the West 
Bank, by the rise of Muslim fundamentalism and by the extension of Syria's 
power. 
</P>
<P>
The PLO declaration was intended to make an independent state the only 
alternative to Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza. King Hussein's 
"divorce" from the West Bank underscored this narrowed choice by removing "the 
Jordanian option" for a Palestinian solution. But "the Jordanian option" was 
precisely the "solution" preferred by Israeli as well as West Bank moderates. 
Its removal weakened the case of Israelis ready to abandon "Judea and Samaria" 
to the right kind of neighboring power. 
</P>
<P>
The effort to present Yasser Arafat as the "moderate" solution was never very 
persuasive, either in Israel or the United States. The case for dealing with 
him declines further as his own power wanes. The spread of Muslim 
fundamentalism on the West Bank and in Gaza and the growing power of Arafat's 
principal rival, Syria's Hafez Assad, mean that Arafat is not in a position to 
guarantee peace -- even if he were inclined to do so. Events in Lebanon and 
Jordan have shown that in this area, tendencies to factionalism, extremism and 
violence are more powerful than Arafat or the Arab League. 
</P>
<P>
In Israel they're describing 1989 as the year the intifada turned on itself. 
The big development was inter-Arab violence, with the number of Palestinian 
"collaborators" hacked to death by other Palestinians variously estimated from 
118 to 160. Obviously these "collaborators" also testify to the PLO's problem 
in commanding the loyalty of all West Bankers. 
</P>
<P>
But there is an oasis of relative tranquility where Arabs and Israelis meet in 
peace if not in harmony. That is Jerusalem. 
</P>
<P>
Life in Jerusalem is nearly normal. The intifada still calls the Arab merchants 
of East Jerusalem out on strike each day. The merchants respond. They close 
their shops at noon and do not reopen until the next morning. But the 
disruption of life is minimal. Street vendors have multiplied. Local 
inhabitants do their shopping in the morning. Schools are open. Public meetings 
are held. The streets are safer than those of most American cities. There were 
only 11 homicides in the first 11 months of this year, about half of them 
related to politics. 
</P>
<P>
The peace process that pacified Jerusalem is Mayor Teddy Kollek's endless 
effort and boundless commitment to provide basic municipal services and 
fairness to all of Jerusalem's inhabitants. 
</P>
<P>
Even Kollek is concerned today about the future of this city he so passionately 
loves. Jerusalem is not mentioned in Baker's five points, he notes, but Arafat 
has said again and again that East Jerusalem must be the capital of a 
Palestinian state. 
</P>
<P>
It cannot be, Kollek vows. He is ready to give Arab citizens of Jerusalem their 
own schools, public services of all kinds and their own vote in municipal 
affairs. He respects their right to remain Jordanian citizens. He promises to 
accord Arabs all the rights a democracy guarantees its citizens. 
</P>
<P>
But even Teddy Kollek has his own non-negotiable demand. "We shan't give up any 
part of Jerusalem, not under any circumstances." 
</P>
<P>
Most Americans are not neutral between the non-negotiable demands of Teddy 
Kollek and Yasser Arafat: The one is a paragon of democracy; the other is a man 
who opposes elections and proclaims himself "the sole representative of the 
Palestinian people." 
</P>
<P>
Maybe before Bush and Baker take on the Arab-Israeli conflict, they should 
practice on something easier, like settling the problem of Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA121589-0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 148783 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 15, 1989, Friday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 7; Column 4; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
640 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WHY NOT SELL AT THE LOCAL PHARMACY?; 
</P>
<P>
DRUGS: SINCE STRICTER LAWS AND TOUGHER ENFORCEMENT HAVE NOT CLEARED THE STREETS 
OF ADDICTS AND PUSHERS, IT'S TIME TO THINK SERIOUSLY ABOUT LEGALIZATION. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WILLIAM M. KUNSTLER, William M. Kunstler is vice president and staff 
attorney for the New York-based Center for Constitutional Rights. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was only 80 years ago, when Congress passed the Harrison Act, that drugs 
became illegal in this country. During America's greatest period of greatest 
expansion, drugs were freely and legitimately obtainable. Opium balls were used 
to put crying babies to sleep; the corner pharmacy catered to any taste in what 
are now called controlled substances. The highest rate of addiction in American 
history was among Union troops during the Civil War. 
</P>
<P>
Once narcotics were prohibited by a battery of increasingly stringent federal 
and state laws, the development of an enormously profitable black market in 
drugs became inevitable. The rate of addiction rose sharply, the result of both 
the forbidden-fruit effect and aggressive, highly motivated pushers. Today, by 
conservative estimates, we have at least 3 million Americans hopelessly hooked 
on heroin, cocaine, crack or hallucinogenics. Roughly 23 million Americans use 
some of these substances each month. 
</P>
<P>
Drug-related crime is steadily increasing, including roughly 750 murders a year 
over turf disputes. Our courts stagger under the weight of 824,000 annual drug 
arrests, and our prisons are glutted with convicted offenders. 
</P>
<P>
No current -- or past -- local or national policy has been able to stem this 
horrendous tide. From Nancy Reagan's cruelly foolish slogan, "Just say no to 
drugs," to the pyramiding of criminal sanctions, including even the death 
penalty, nothing has proved to be even slightly effective in either curbing 
addiction or preventing importation and sale. 
</P>
<P>
In early 1988, Kurt Schmoke, a former federal prosecutor and the newly elected 
mayor of Baltimore, addressing a meeting of the U.S. Conference of Mayors, 
startled his audience by recommending that there be "a national debate about 
decriminalizing drugs." Recently, former Secretary of State George P. Shultz, 
now teaching economics at Stanford University, suggested that "we should at 
least be willing to debate (these) issues." And this week, Robert W. Sweet, a 
federal judge in Manhattan and former assistant U.S. attorney, refocused 
attention on the issue when he called for the legalization of drugs. 
</P>
<P>
Last February, a New York state senator, Joseph L. Galiber, introduced a 
drug-decriminalization bill loosely modeled after laws in effect in Great 
Britain for almost half a century. While it has no chance of passage, given the 
public's current overwhelming antipathy to legalization, it deserves serious 
attention and consideration. 
</P>
<P>
Under its provisions, a five-member Controlled Substance Authority would be 
created, with power to license physicians and pharmacists who met stringent 
qualification to sell drugs legally to persons older than 21. No licenses would 
be issued to applicants whose offices or places of business were within 200 
feet of schools or houses of worship. 
</P>
<P>
In introducing his bill, Galiber argued that "by decriminalizing the sale, 
possession and use of controlled substances, we won't end the demand (for 
drugs), but we can take the huge profits out and remove the heinous criminal 
elements. Then we can attempt serious efforts in combating drugs through 
education and treatment." 
</P>
<P>
It is obviously impossible to predict whether the proponents of legalization 
are on the right track. But since criminalization has not worked, no matter how 
rigorous or harsh its enforcement, is it not time to accept the suggestion of 
Shultz and Sweet, among others, and initiate a national debate on the issue? Or 
shall we continue to treat drugs as a problem for the criminal-justice system 
rather than as a health question, with all the attendant misery, cost and 
futility, without even exploring what well might be a workable alternative? It 
simply makes no sense to keep knocking on a door that thus far has led to 
nowhere when there may be others that open onto more productive avenues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA121589-0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 148784 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 15, 1989, Friday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
