<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO SPORTS ET CETERA; 
</P>
<P>
AZTECS AVOID PADRES, MOVE UTEP GAME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CURT HOLBREICH FOOTBALL Hollywood is interested in filming a story about 
former Vista High and 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
San Diego State has resolved a scheduling conflict with the Padres at San Diego 
Jack Murphy Stadium by moving its home football game with Texas El Paso next 
season to Nov. 24. 
</P>
<P>
The game had been scheduled to be played Sept. 22, but the Padres took that 
Saturday night date for the second of a three-game series with the Cincinnati 
Reds. 
</P>
<P>
The switch of the UTEP game to what had been an open date for SDSU was made 
this week during the Western Athletic Conference winter meetings in Denver, 
Jeff Hurd, the WAC's associate commissioner, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Hurd also said that conference athletic directors voted unanimously to return 
to round-robin scheduling in football beginning with the 1991 season. This will 
end a scheduling format adopted in 1986, and instituted this past season, that 
allowed four schools each season to play seven rather than eight conference 
games. 
</P>
<P>
This allowed schools to use the extra date to schedule another nonconference 
game, but Hurd said athletic directors were concerned that the uneven number of 
conference games put schools at a disadvantage when it came to determining the 
WAC champion and the Holiday Bowl berth. 
</P>
<P>
SDSU used the uneven scheduling to eliminate a home-and-home series with 
Colorado State for 1989 and 1990. The change will not affect the Aztecs until 
1993, when they again would have been permitted to drop a conference game. 
</P>
<P>
The plan still must be approved by the conference presidents at their annual 
meeting in June 8-11 in Tucson, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
In other action, the 1991 conference basketball tournament was awarded to 
Wyoming. CURT HOLBREICHFOOTBALL Hollywood is interested in filming a story 
about former Vista High and Colorado quarterback Sal Aunese, who died of 
inoperable stomach cancer Sept. 23. Beverly Hills agent Ed Hookstratten has 
been retained by the Aunese family to represent its dealings with movie studios 
interested in the life of the late athlete. "I don't see it being done as a 
picture on TV; it's larger than that," Hookstratten said. "It's a theatrical 
motion picture and should be handled by the finest in the business." When he 
became ill in the spring of 1989, Aunese's teammates dedicated their season to 
him, then finished 11-0 and ranked No. 1 nationally. The Buffaloes can win the 
national championship by beating Notre Dame in the Orange Bowl on Jan. 
1.BASKETBALL Howard Wright, a former Patrick Henry all-county player, returned 
to his high school and made his first six shots of the second half to break 
open a close game, leading Athletes In Action to a 114-92 exhibition victory 
over Christian Heritage College. The former Patriot who went on to play at 
Stanford scored a game-high 28 points and had eight rebounds. The Hawks were 
led by Mark Kraatz and Brad Soucie, who each had 23 points. Athletes In Action 
is now 8-21 and their collegiate tour will end Saturday at Loyola Marymount. 
</P>
</TEXT>
