<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE 'PRICE OF A PAL' STRIKES A CHORD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Regarding veterinary costs, the subject is a microcosm of the dilemma with 
human medical costs. 
</P>
<P>
The advance of medical insurance and charity meant the doctor did not have to 
discuss his bill with the patient. It was sent along to the insurance company 
and the full amount was paid. 
</P>
<P>
The insured didn't care how much the doctor was charging because the insurance 
company paid. The insurance companies simply raised their premiums. The 
employers who paid those premiums used the tax system as a cost of doing 
business. Ever since socialized medicine has been discussed, putting a lid on 
how much will be paid to the medical establishment, doctors have been 
frightened into charging more and more to reap as much money as they can before 
the free lunch is over. They have diversified into drug stores, hospitals, 
insurance companies (talk about monopolies). 
</P>
<P>
Now the veterinarians have started down the same path. Your article states that 
there is a "recession" among the veterinary profession. Maybe people simply 
cannot afford to take their pets to pet hospitals as much as before. Insurance 
and charity are the cause of inflation for the care of animals, not the cure. 
</P>
<P>
Keep the veterinary doctors competitive by putting pressure on them to keep 
costs reasonable instead of seeking ways to protect a guaranteed financial 
expectation. There are no sacred, immune professions. 
</P>
<P>
KATHERINE A. KEYS, North Hollywood 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
