<TEXT>
<P>
Hollywood Memorabilia Up for Grabs: Ever wanted to dress up as Judah Ben-Hur 
facing off against Rome's greatest charioteers in the Colosseum? If so, put in 
your bid this afternoon to Sotheby's in New York, which is offering these and 
59 other items in a special auction of Hollywood memorabilia. Among the more 
talked-about pieces on the block at 2 p.m. today are a red sequined evening 
gown worn by Marilyn Monroe in "Gentlemen Prefer Blondes" (expected to fetch 
$8,000 to $12,000), a bowler hat worn by Charlie Chaplin while filming "City 
Lights" ($6,000 to $8,000) and Judy Garland's blue-and-white cotton dress in 
"The Wizard of Oz" ($20,000 to $25,000). Also to be auctioned is the 
17-by-37-foot backdrop used by Alfred Hitchcock in his 1945 film, "Spellbound." 
The massive painting, designed by surrealist Salvador Dali, is expected to 
bring the auction's top price: an estimated $80,000. SHAUNA SNOW 
</P>
