<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: WESTMINSTER; 
</P>
<P>
FIREWORKS RECEIVE 4TH OF JULY REPRIEVE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG HERNANDEZ 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fireworks will be legal in Westminster during next year's Fourth of July, 
regardless of the outcome of a June referendum. 
</P>
<P>
The City Council voted 4 to 1 this week to place the referendum on the June, 
1990, ballot to let voters decide whether fireworks should be banned in the 
city. 
</P>
<P>
They also voted that the ban, if approved, would not go into effect until next 
August, so that organizations selling fireworks could do so one last time. 
</P>
<P>
The council had the option of calling for a special election in March, which 
would have cost about $38,000, or placing the issue on the ballot during a 
primary or general election at a cost of about $13,000. 
</P>
<P>
The referendum is the result of efforts made by a citizens group that collected 
the 3,734 signatures needed to qualify the referendum for the ballot. The group 
began collecting the signatures after the council approved a fireworks-banning 
ordinance on Sept. 12. 
</P>
<P>
The council rescinded the ordinance on Nov. 28 to place the issue before the 
voters. GREG HERNANDEZ 
</P>
</TEXT>
