<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: SANTA ANA; 
</P>
<P>
LOTTO WINNER'S LUCK RUBS OFF ON COUPLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TONY MARCANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This Christmas, somewhere in Orange County -- presumably Santa Ana -- someone 
won't have to pout, and won't have to cry, but he or she will probably shout. 
Want to know why? 
</P>
<P>
Santa Claus is coming to town -- with $10.1 million in his sack. 
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, one lucky person walked into a Santa Ana liquor store and 
selected the numbers 30, 49, 3, 24, 47 and 46 for Wednesday night's Lotto 
drawing. Whoever it was didn't know it at the time, but that person walked out 
with more than $10 million to spend on Christmas gifts. Or anything else, for 
that matter. 
</P>
<P>
It was not immediately known who hit the jackpot. 
</P>
<P>
The winner, the first ever to pick six of six numbers at a Santa Ana Lotto 
outlet, did not come forward to claim the mega-prize Thursday, said state 
lottery spokesman John Schade. 
</P>
<P>
Another winner of sorts will also have a very merry Christmas. 
</P>
<P>
June Park, co-owner with her husband of the Santa Liquor Mart and Deli at 652 
S. Harbor Blvd., was $50,500 wealthier Thursday just for selling the winning 
ticket to the state's newest millionaire. 
</P>
<P>
In her neat, well-stocked shop, Park was so giddy that in trying to introduce 
her husband, she said, "Um, um, James Park -- I'm so excited, I forgot my 
husband's name!" 
</P>
<P>
For the Parks, both 32, the jackpot was the culmination of the American dream. 
</P>
<P>
They both arrived in the United States about 15 years ago, June from Seoul, 
South Korea, and James, who is also of Korean descent, from Sao Paulo, Brazil. 
They scrimped and saved and scraped together enough money to open their 
business 2 1/2 years ago, and they bought a home in Hacienda Heights. 
</P>
<P>
"I just sold my home last Sunday night," June Park said. "We were deciding on 
where to buy a new house. That's why the timing was so great." 
</P>
<P>
Park said she and her husband will use the windfall to place a down payment on 
a new, bigger home, for themselves and their two children, Natalie, 10, and 
Alexander, 4. 
</P>
<P>
She also said she will share some of the Lotto loot with her employees. 
</P>
<P>
In addition to those practical and charitable plans, Park, like all people with 
"found money," may not be able to resist a splurge. 
</P>
<P>
"Maybe I'll throw a party," she said. TONY MARCANO 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, June and James Park, owners of Santa Liquor Market &amp; Deli of Santa 
Ana, will receive $50,500 for selling a $10.1-million winning Lotto ticket for 
Wednesday drawing. JOHN FUNG / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
