<HEADLINE>
<P>
FORMALLY SPEAKING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOOYOUNG LEE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taffeta, satin and sequins for the girls; pegged pants and fancy cummerbunds 
for the guys. 
</P>
<P>
These were the fashions most prominent at Brea-Olinda High School's winter 
formal dance Dec. 9 at Plaza de Cafes in Newport Beach. 
</P>
<P>
Most of the dresses were strapless or spaghetti-strapped, and almost all were 
cut above the knee. Some girls went for metallic golds, silvers, blues or 
greens. Popular colors tended to be the darker ones -- black, royal blue and 
jade -- though some opted for pastels. "I like the pink dresses," said Archana 
Hardas, a Brea-Olinda junior. 
</P>
<P>
Velvet was still the most desired fabric, though only a few actually wore 
dresses made of it. "Velvet dresses with ruffles, either sleeveless or with big 
sleeves, are nice," junior Chrissy Barlet said. "But there is a limit to the 
ruffles, as nobody likes too many frills and bows." 
</P>
<P>
Senior Wendy Winslow said the fashion key was to keep it simple. "Tight, short 
dresses are in, but they have to be simple," she said. "Wear a lot of 
accessories." 
</P>
<P>
For guys, it was much easier: Black tuxedos and patent leather shoes. Of 
course, bow ties and cummerbunds had to match the girl's dress. 
</P>
<P>
"Most wore short, fitted jackets rather than long ones," junior Ray Jordan 
said. "Though some did show up in tails." JOOYOUNG LEE 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Fritz Wickman and Wendy Winslow enjoy the dancing at Brea-Olinda High 
School's winter formal dance. ; Photo, Jack Emerson and Chau Tran break for 
punch. ; Photo, Shoshanna Solomon and Ray Jordan sit one out. ; Photo, Erin 
Crabb and Mark Sewell at the Plaza de Cafes. ROD BOREN / For The Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
